snippet.textDisplay:
We had this issue -- or rather my friend had this issue -- back in 2011.

At my previous company, back before Y2K and the world going crazy about 2 vs 4 digit years, dates were STORED numerically as 990428. On reports we'd format them in US Standard 04/28/99. Well, couldn't have a null value in a date field, so in one particular area of the system, they used 11111 for a placeholder. However, on reports, we WANTED that to appear as a null value, so that function that turned 990428 into 04/28/99, returned a null value for 111111.

This of course broke HORRIBLY on November 11, 2011 and my friend who was still working there called laughing in hysterics when all the reports using that field broke that morning. Good times.

snippet.textDisplay:
This literally happened to me on Monday December 30. I work at a bank, and one of our payment systems was sending out transactions marked '30december2020' which were rejected by the receiving system.

And the root cause was literally this EXACT bug. ISO 8601 week dates because someone formatted the year with 'YYYY' but should have used 'yyyy'.

I really wish I saw this video the day it came out. It would have saved me a few hours.
